---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import MoonStar from '../../components/decor/MoonStar.astro';
import Sparkles from '../../components/decor/Sparkles.astro';
import PracticeRoom from '../../components/PracticeRoom/PracticeRoom';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Practice Room · AI Roleplay"
  description="A leader practices a hard 1:1 with an AI-played teammate who reacts in the moment. Live read on how it's landing, every turn streamed to the LRS as xAPI, and an AI coaching debrief at the end."
>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden bg-paper paper-bg">
    <MoonStar class="absolute top-10 left-6 sm:left-12 w-10 sm:w-14 h-auto opacity-90 hidden sm:block" />
    <Sparkles class="hidden md:block absolute bottom-8 right-10 w-28 lg:w-36 h-auto opacity-80 pointer-events-none" />
    <div class="relative max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-16 sm:py-20">
      <p class="font-display text-sm uppercase tracking-widest text-cocoa/50 mb-3">What AI unlocks · scenario-based practice</p>
      <h1 class="font-display font-semibold text-cocoa text-4xl sm:text-5xl lg:text-6xl leading-tight tracking-tight">
        You can read about hard conversations. Or you can <span class="italic text-primary-600">have one</span>.
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-cocoa/75 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        Slide decks can't rehearse a moment that talks back. This one can. You walk in as a leader coaching a teammate
        who's quietly checked out, and practice the real skill: make it safe, listen before fixing, name the pattern
        without blame. The teammate reacts to what you actually say, and every turn streams to the LRS as xAPI, so the
        behavior is measurable, not the click.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>


  <!-- The experience -->
  <section class="bg-cream-50 py-12 sm:py-16 border-t border-cocoa/10">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6">
      <PracticeRoom client:load />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why it matters -->
  <section class="bg-paper border-t border-cocoa/10 py-14">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-5">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-cocoa/15 bg-cream-50 p-5">
          <p class="font-display font-semibold text-cocoa mb-1.5">Practice, not exposure</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-cocoa/70 leading-relaxed">The first time a manager has this conversation shouldn't be with a real person who's actually struggling. Here they can take a wrong turn, watch it land badly, and run it again.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-cocoa/15 bg-cream-50 p-5">
          <p class="font-display font-semibold text-cocoa mb-1.5">The thing only AI does</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-cocoa/70 leading-relaxed">A branching scenario has a fixed set of right answers. A model plays a person. It improvises, gets defensive, opens up, and the debrief reads back what <em>you</em> actually said.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-cocoa/15 bg-cream-50 p-5">
          <p class="font-display font-semibold text-cocoa mb-1.5">Measurable behavior</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-cocoa/70 leading-relaxed">Every turn is an xAPI statement: the approach taken, the read at that moment, the rubric at the end. It lands in the LRS and rolls up to the <a href="/dashboard" class="text-primary-600 font-semibold hover:underline">manager dashboard</a> as Kirkpatrick L3.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-6 text-sm text-cocoa/55 max-w-3xl">
        The conversation runs live against a model when one is connected; on this static page it runs as a guided
        version off the same design so it's always fully playable. Sam is fictional. The burnout pattern is not.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
